In this trend prediction, I do not think that people have just one hypothesis (e.g., increasing or decreasing trend). Me too. My prediction was based on multiple hypotheses. 
1. The increasing trend will remain the same in the begining of COVID-19. 
   (counter hypotheiss) the increasing trend will be reverted to the decreasing or plateau trend. 
2. In the middle stage, there will be a sudden drop
    (CH) in the middle stage, the trend will remain the same
3. In the later stage, there will be an increasing trend (as it has been so far). 
     (CH) in the later stage, there will be a decreasing or plateau trend.

I think if the disease had spread more rapidly throughout the U.S., then it might have made people endorse more (currently perceived as) liberal positions to start, thus giving the country a different base from which to move.  If that were the case, the U.S. would be slightly more liberal right now politically.  Of course, the federal government might have reacted differently too – but it would have likely changed the dynamic quite a bit, altering the lead-up trends.

If that were the case, the U.S. would be slightly more liberal right now politically. I think if the disease had spread more rapidly throughout the U.S., then it might have reduced partisanship and led to a completely different starting point.  In our model, experience with the disease reduces partisanship (people care less about their political goals and motives when their families’ or their own health is in question). Ironically, it is possible that the restrictions that conservatives oppose might have actually increased the partisan divide by reducing the spread of the disease.

The clearest counterfactual would be the pandemic not occurring, and if that had happened we'd expect to see more stable life satisfaction. The other key counterfactual is that if the pandemic had been handled better in early days it potentially wouldn't have had as much of a negative impact on life satisfaction.

The events related to the pandemic obviously are important here, though the pandemic itself may not be as important as the ways people have responded to the pandemic, making something that isn't in-and-of-itself partisan into a partisan issue. So obviously with the pandemic hadn't occurred things would be different, but it's how politicians and partisan public figures responded to the pandemic that would be shaping trends in political ideology.

So obviously with the pandemic hadn't occurred things would be different, but it's how politicians and partisan public figures responded to the pandemic that would be shaping trends in political ideology.
How Trump/Republicans politicized the pandemic could lead to a bit more polarization, but we're already near a ceiling so Trump/Republicans responding differently may not have mattered much.

I don't really expect any change to have occurred even in light of the pandemic (and how the pandemic has been handled in the U.S., which includes pushing responsibility on women in a shift toward traditionalism in part due to lack of governmental support in response to the pandemic).

Yes, the pandemic has pushed people into situations where they're reverting to traditional gender roles to deal with new situations, but I doubt this will have a huge impact on explicit gender bias. People have long ended up doing more or less gender traditional things as a result of changes in their lives that make it easier or harder for women to have opportunities outside of home and childcare responsibilities.

column7:
Given that our prediction does not assume only a minuscule change in implicit bias, any counterfactual would induce a change that increased or decreased bias. An increase in bias would have occurred if there were a large number of public images and a great expansion of public discourse that linked Asian (or Asian Americans) to a much more negative evaluation. Surely, there had been an ongoing negative evaluation for many years, including at the highest levels of government. Well-publicized events such as murder and mayhem committed by Asians on U.S. soil might have rendered such representation even more negative than they currently are. 
Possibly, events associating Asians and Asian Americans with a positive evaluation, such as it is accorded to popular movie stars or musicians might have reduced the anti-Asian American implicit bias, though it is hard to imagine a star big enough and well-known enough to achieve such a widespread positive evaluation. Moreover, because the IAT taps primarily highly inert associations, it stands to reason that such stars/heros would need to present in the public mind for an extended period of time.
By the same token, this bias could have been reduced, if there had been a dramatic, pervasive and likely emotionally charged even that associated being white, with a negative association (e.g., discovery of blatant and pervasive white racism in government, which at least somewhat undermined the favorability of whites even in the minds of white Americans).

If President Trump had embraced the crisis, taken it seriously, and in January/early February had squared with the American people as to what this means, he would have emerged as the unquestioned hero. He would have faced Democratic attacks that would have likely been ridiculed when it would have become apparent, how well the U.S. was addressing the problem - when so many other countries were suffered severely under the pandemic. This would have been a risky move, among other things because prevention is never glorious. However, the contrast with many other countries around the world would have regained the U.S. a lot of international respect, and the apparent pissing contest with China (over who handled the crisis better) would have been decided in the U.S.'s favor. Especially in an election year, this could have significantly boosted Republican support and weakened the appeal of the Democratic candidate. It would have allowed Americans to rally around the (Republican) flag. It would have also force Democrats to side with the Republican President on matters of public support for businesses and workers. Needless to say, this is a counterfactual that definitely did not happen.

I actually think that the trajectories are largely resilient to most and almost all possible events.

If there were any major event, I would think that there be a large war with a number of casualties would reduce life satisfaction (and there's some unpublished work to suggest this).

Even large, race-specific events have little influence on implicit bias (e.g., the election of Obama for African American bias). COVID-19 might have affected this but I actually don't even think that's the case. So, no counterfactuals could change my prediction!

the US economy was doing remarkably well until it was hit by the corona virus crisis but life satisfaction cannot be a factor of only the impact of the corona virus.

the corona virus hit only on the last month of the data and its impact will possibly be seen in three months when the new school year starts.

thus, a significant drop in retail sales or a market crash at least two months prior to the corona virus would have affected the forecast but none of this occurred in sufficient time in the past to reflect on a significant drop on the forecasts; should it have happened then a lower value for the first few months of the forecasting horizon would have been obtained in the forecasts.

The emergence of COVID19 pandemic has shattered the whole complexion of the world, over the past few months. This was something that the world hasn’t seen before.  The time series forecasting models used in work takes past observations and extrapolate the patterns into the future. These models are suitable when the data are accurate, and the future is similar to the past. However, since the observations during the COVID19 pandemic have not been seen by the models before, the models may not achieve their full potential in accuracy.  Whereas, if the COVID19 would have been already encountered before (between 2017 and 2019), then the forecasts models could have incorporated this, when generating the forecasts. Therefore, the counterfactual of the presence of "COVID19 Pandemic" is an essential event to be accounted for when generating forecasts.

However, since the observations during the COVID19 pandemic have not been seen by the models before, the models may not achieve their full potential in accuracy.  Whereas, if the COVID19 would have been already encountered before (between 2017 and 2019), then the forecasts models could have incorporated this, when generating the forecasts. Therefore, the counterfactual of the presence of "COVID19 Pandemic" is an essential event to be accounted, when generating the forecasts.

Compared to the US, many countries (e.g., Japan, South Korea, Taiwan, Australia, Germany) have experienced lower COVID-19 prevalence and lower increases in the rate of unemployment. Successful strategies vary widely but include early lockdowns, widespread mask wearing and testing, and extensive contact tracing. A key counterfactual event that could have occurred between December 2019 and April 2020 would have been for the WHO and CDC to have announced as early as January 2020 that cloth masks shown be worn in public places. This would have reduced COVID-19 prevalence in the US, allowed greater economic activity and fewer jobs lost. This counterfactual event would increase the predicted life satisfaction over the next year for every month but would not substantially change the overall trajectory.

In our model, we include race/police brutality protests as a reason for why polarization will increase in the summer months of 2020. We also suggest that the isolation related to the COVID pandemic will contribute to an increase in polarization. If either of these events had not occurred, we believe that polarization would be several percentage points lower for all of our predictions in 2020.
If a woman of color had received the presidential nomination, rather than Biden, then explicit bias in the upcoming year may be higher than estimated; as was the case with Obama (Piston, 2010).

If a woman had won the democratic nomination, we may have observed slight increases in our explicit bias projection, as well-performing women may engender social identity threats in men, promoting sexist responses from men (Bosson, Vandello, Burnaford, Weaver, & Arzu Wasti, 2009; Dahl, Vescio, & Weaver, 2015).

The life satisfaction during the recession of 2008 could be relevant and trajectories can be extracted from that event and used as extra input for the prediction. However, we finally decided not to use that at this stage. 
The effect of implemented policies can be considered as other counterfactuals as one can make predictions based on the expected consequence of each. For example, the US closed the borders earlier. The US enforced individual isolation at the airport. The US suggested wearing masks earlier, etc.
We are planning to include more of the counterfactuals factors in the next stages of the prediction.

Donald Trump’s tweets and general attitude towards China/pandemic. For example, on March 18, Trump tweeted: “I always treated the Chinese Virus very seriously, and have done a very good job from the beginning, including my very early decision to close the ‘borders’ from China - against the wishes of almost all.” The very fact that he refers to COVID-19 as the “Chinese virus” may give citizens the false sense that the circumstances in the US are entirely China’s fault. Such political efforts to blame the virus on China might have allowed for more explicit bias towards Asians among the American public. If Trump had assumed responsibility to fight the virus locally in the US, without suggesting China is responsible for the pandemic, explicit Asian bias might not have increased to its present levels.
